WHAT'S CHANGEDSnowflake Inc. (SNOW.N)FromToPrice Target$262.00$272.00

A strong core + traction in adj markets results in FY26 product revenue growth outlook rising to \(+27\%\) vs. \(+25\%\) prior. Remain. OW as SNOW is best way to play the data modernization theme in Software.

Q2 product rev growth accelerated to \(+31.5\%\) YoY on a days- adjusted basis, supported by a strong core and outperformance in new products. Q3 product rev guidance came in ahead of consensus and the outlook for FY26, now calls for \(+27\%\) YoY growth versus \(+25\%\) prior Strong consumption trends reflect ongoing improvement in the core Analytics business but Data Engineering, Cortex and Apps & Collaboration outperformed as well. We see data transformation initiatives to unlock AI as one of the key IT budget priorities and see Snowflake as the best way to play the theme Remain OW and raise PT to \(\) 272\(as Q2 results give incremental confidence towards our thesis on SNOW delivering best in class cloud growth + improving margins

Acceleration Back to \(30\% +\) Growth Comes Early. The business transformation effort led by CEO Sridhar Ramaswamy moved to a higher gear in Q2 as product revenue accelerated to \(+32\%\) YoY rom \(+28\%\) (on a days adjusted basis) in Q1. There were 3 themes that stuc out to us on the earnings call. First, echoing the narrative from recent quarters, strength in Q2 was driven mostly by the core Analytics business, as customers are investing aggressively in data modernization/ transformation initiatives - not just to move to the cloud, but increasingly because progress other AI ambitions is impossible without them. Second, while the core continues to be the main driver, Snowflake saw outperformance across its other 3 segments as well, including Data Engineering, Apps & Collaboration and AI. On AI, the demand signals are screening positive as roughly half of Snowflake's customer base is using one of the company's AI services every week. A related point is that Snowflake's AI capabilities are bringing in new customers as AI influenced \(50\%\) of new logos acquired in the quarter. Third, the improvement in growth is not coming at the expense of margins - the company delivered an \(11\%\) operating margin in Q2, which was well ahead of consensus of \(8\%\) , and was up \(\sim 600\) bps YoY. Having delivered a robust Q2, FY26 product revenue guidance was raised by \(\) 70\(million to

\(\) 4,395\(million - more than\) \ \(48\) million beat in Q2 and implying growth of \(+27\%\) YoY, up from \(+25\%\) previously. While large data migrations was a boost to consumption in Q2 (which management discounts in the outlook), we still see product revenue poised for further upside as 2H guidance implies a \(- 24\%\) YoY decline in net- new product revenue after net- new product revenue grew \(+61\%\) in 1H. Acknowledging that valuation at \(\sim 13.6x\) CY26 sales (0.46x adjusted for growth) is not cheap, we remain firmly Ow Snowflake as we see the company as the best way to play the theme of data transformation, which we believe to be one of the highest priority budget initiatives into CY26 and beyond.

- Product Revenue Growth Accelerates to \(30\% +\) . Product revenue of \(1,090.5M\) million beat consensus by \(\sim 4.6\%\) . This resulted in \(+31.5\%\) YoY growth on a days-adjusted basis – an acceleration from \(+28\%\) in Q1. Net-new product revenue grew \(+136\%\) YoY off an easy YoY compare and benefited from an extra day in 2Q26 vs. 1Q26 compared to the same period last year.- Growth In Customer Base Remains Robust. In Q2, Snowflake drove a \(21\%\) YoY increase in net new customers added, bringing the total customer count to 12,062. What's more, Snowflake also saw incremental acceleration in customers spending \(>\) 1M on an LTM basis, adding 50 in total, and up \(30\%\) YoY (vs. \(26\%\) YoY in Q1).- Q3 Product Revenue Guidance Slightly Ahead of Consensus. Q3 product revenue guidance of \(1,125 - 1,130\) million (implying \(25\% - 26\%\) YoY) came in slightly ahead of consensus of \(1,23.5\) million / \(24.8\%\) YoY.- FY26 Product Revenue Outlook Raised (Again). Exiting Q2, Snowflake's updated product revenue now sits at \(4,395\) million, implying \(\sim 27\%\) YoY growth (from \(4,325\) million / \(25\%\) prior). Relative to prior guidance, this implies a \(70m\) raise to the year, ahead of the Q2 beat of \(53\) million (vs. the midpoint). While our 2H'26 estimates remain largely unchanged (having been slightly about consensus into the print), the updated outlook came in \(\sim\) 53 million ahead of consensus of \(4,342.2\) million.- Q3 Product Revenue Upside Driven by Strength In Core; Complemented by Outperformance Across New Categories. In Q3, management noted that the majority of outperformance was attributable to strength in core data warehousing in the back of strong migration trends (and negligible contribution from Crunchy Data). This was further reflected in TTM net retention, which ticked up to \(125\%\) (vs. \(124\%\) in Q1). However, commentary on new product trends was also a positive, as Data Engineering, AI, and Apps and Collaboration also coming in ahead of expectations. In terms of profitability, the operating margin outlook was raised to \(9\%\) (from \(8\%\) ), while the adjusted FCF margin outlook remains unchanged at \(25\%\) .

- Hiring Continues to Accelerate. Total headcount grew \(15\%\) YoY (VS. \(13\%\) YoY in 1Q26), with total adds 529 (vs. 406 in 1Q26). Within the mix, headcount growth continues to be mainly driven by S&M (+25% YoY, vs. \(18\%\) YoY in Q1) – with Snowflake having added more S&M headcount in the LGM

than the prior two years combined (on a net basis that said, management did note that S&M hiring is 1H weighted. Q2 FCF Misses. Q2 adjusted FCF of 67.8 million came in below MSe/ consensus expectations of \(87.8 million / 108.7 million, at a 5.9\%\) margin (down \(\sim 170\) bps YoY). However, management reiterated its FY26 adjusted FCF margin outlook of \(\sim 25\%\) , continuing to expect overall FCF to be 2H weighted.

Raising PT to \(\) 272\(from\) \ \(262\) . As we wrote about in our recent upgrade to Overweight (from Equal- weight), we believe that enterprise prioritization of modernizing data infrastructure will support stabilization (and eventual re- acceleration) in the core data warehousing business, complemented by ramping product cycles in data engineering and AI - that will ultimately support a durable growth profile for the foreseeable future. Q2 results, which showed strong performance in the core and outperformance in newer areas provide further confidence in this view. As a result, we are modestly revising our price target higher. We arrive at our revised \(\) 272\(price target by applying a\) \sim 48x \(multiple to our CY30e FCF estimate of\) \ \(3,443\) million, discounted back to CY26 at an \(11.1\%\) WACC - implying \(1.85x\) on a growth adjusted basis (CY28- CY30 FCF CAGR). On topline, our price target implies \(\sim 17.7x\) CY26 revenue, or \(0.72x\) growth adjusted basis. Our multiples reflect a premium to high growth infrastructure peers, justified by improvement in growth, margins and traction in areas such as data engineering as well as AI use cases.
Assessing the Snowflake Print

After a few years of decelerating growth and mounting investor concerns on its positioning for Al/ML, Snowflake's secular growth prospects have improved under the leadership of CEO Sridhar Ramaswamy Under his tenure, Snowflake has become a sharper executing organization across both sales, go- to market and product engineering which has translated to stabilization in product revenue growth in the high 20's. We believe Snowflake has settled on a strategy on how it will successfully capitalize on \(\) 300+\(billion market opportunity giving us confidence in durable\) 20\%+\(growth with consistently expanding operating margins.
